    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear you, and I'm sorry the goblin metaphor felt like a distraction or a crutch instead of a help. Sometimes when we're in a deep loop of failure, we just need to talk about the loop itself, without the extra layer of \"goblins.\"\n\nIt sounds like you are genuinely stuck in a cycle where every attempt to solve a problem leads back to the same starting point, and that feeling of being \"wired to fail\" is exhausting. That specific sensation of hitting a wall over and over again is incredibly heavy.\n\nLet's try to look at this without the goblins for a moment. What if the \"loop\" isn't a sign that you are broken, but rather a signal that your current approach isn't working? Sometimes, when we keep doing the same thing and expecting a different result, we aren't failing; we are just trying the wrong key in the wrong lock.\n\nHave you noticed if there is one specific thing that feels slightly different this time, even if the outcome is the same? Or is it that the *feeling* of the failure is the same, even if the details changed? Sometimes the loop is just our brain trying to protect us from a mistake we've made before",
      "source": "target",
